<font color="#FF0000">DEMODULATION ATTEMPT</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jun 12 13:34:24 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Gerald:<br><br>
In a society where speech is truly free, there would be no such thing as &quot;language that is too extreme or provocative.&quot;<br>
After all, WHO defines the standards or norms by which language is so judged, and by what authority?  <br><br>
Truly tolerant people would not be incensed, but rather intrigued by language that the intolerant and narrow-minded, those uncomfortable with truly free speech, find &quot;offensive.&quot;   These tolerant people would examine the content of these so-called &quot;extreme&quot; statements, mull them over for awhile, and then either refute or just dismiss them if they seemed to be without any recognizable truth-value.  They would not attempt to prohibit or punish the people who make them, because they recognize that the act of examining and evaluating them is therapeutic, in that it stimulates and provokes critical thinking, and keeps the truly free speech system healthy.<br><br>
This is just a rehash of the old playground taunt:  Sticks &amp; stones may break my bones, but names will never harm me.  But the attitude it describes has to be the norm in our society if the search for truth is to be without restrictions, and therefore a worthwhile pursuit.  <br><br>
I realize that all Congressmen and Senators are human beings, but because they all collaborate with and benefit from a system that is stinkingly corrupt, one that has made obvious whores of some of their number, they are equally guilty.  If there are any good men in the Congress, then by remaining silent and going along with the system, they have allowed the evil to flourish, and by tolerating, even working to benefit, the whores in their midst, they have become no better than whores themselves.<br><br>
All it would take is for just one Senator or Congressman to state that he will run his reelection with funds only from his own rather generous salary, rather than spend huge amounts of time drumming up contributions.  Even if he lost, the statement would be made that he, at least, was moving out of the cathouse.  Until that happens, I will continue to use my &quot;extreme&quot; terminology when referring to any of them with the idea that the contempt of the voters make work, where the integrity of the candidates fails, to push the system toward reform.<br><br>
As for the American Legion, there is, in fact, an interesting discussion of this contrast you mention, between the &quot;Americanism&quot; of the American Legion, and that envisioned by Madison, in Pencak's book...first chapter, I think.<br><br>
While &quot;divine right of kings&quot; may have been discredited in England by the time of the American Revolution, it was still alive and well in most of the other European, and Asian countries of the time.  Wasn't the Monroe Doctrine proclaimed in order to warn off a alliance of absolutist powers from re-establishing colonies among the liberated nations of this hemisphere?  And to what extent was George III, himself,  responsible for limiting the citizenship of his American subjects, either directly or through Parliamentary manipulations?  Did he not still have powers beyond that of other men of his time because he was the king?  After all, he was raised with a German, and therefore, absolutist idea of his role in society as king. I don't believe the notion of absolute monarchy died a sudden death in England in 1610.<br>

